             <td><b><font size="+1">Spinosity</font></b> <br>








       The development of spines is commonly thought of as primarily a defensive 
   adaptation, and increased spinosity is seen in a wide variety of trilobite 
   species. Alternate hypotheses for the adaptive significance of spines include
   stabilization structures on a loose silty substrate (<i>e.g. </i>genal 
spines  of trinucleid Asaphida, such as <i>Ampyx</i>, below), and flotation/stabilization 
   structures for slow-swimming taxa (<i>e.g.,</i> odontopleuroid Lichida 
such  as <i>Leonaspis</i> at left). Spines may originate from just about any
part  of the exoskeleton, especially the margins. Sometimes these patterns 
provide  consistent and diagnostic characters for higher classification (for 
example,  the pattern of pygidial spines among odontopleuroid <a href="ordlichida.htm" target="lichida">Lichida</a>).  However, as seen in 
  the spinose species below, development of spines occurs  in many orders 
of  trilobites.&nbsp;</td>








           </tr>








                           
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
