           <tr valign="top">








             <td><img src="Wujiajia.jpg" border="0" height="233" width="200">
                                                       
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      
      <center><i><font size="-1">Wujiajiania sutherlandii</font></i></center>








             </td>








             <td><b><font size="+1">Olenimorph</font></b> <br>








       Thin exoskeleton, increased numbers of thoracic segments, and a widened, 
   flat body form is associated with benthic habitats marked by low oxygen 
 and high sulphur compound concentrations. Fortey suggests that <b>olenimorphs</b> 
   (so named because many of the <a href="ordptychopariida.htm" target="ptych">Ptychopariida Suborder Olenina</a> have this form) may represent
   the first symbiotic relationships with sulphur-eating bacteria as a <a href="feeding.htm" target="feeding">feeding  strategy</a>. The numerous transverse
thoracic pleurae presumeably overlaid  a series of laterally extended gill
exites, maximizing oxygen absorption       <u>and</u> providing a large surface
area upon (or within) which symbiotic bacteria could live.</td>








           </tr>








                           
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  </tbody>       
</table>








             
<table border="0" cols="5" width="100%">








         <tbody>








